Given Planckâs constant miniscule size, this is relatively accurate, so the calculated work function and threshold are close to the actual values of the metal.

 The error of an order of magnitude in Planckâs constant can be attributed to a few factors. It is possible that the filters used were smudged from peopleâs fingers, distorting the light. From the data collected, the trend shows that the values of the red spectra have a higher wavelength and lower frequency/energy change than the violet spectra has. This means that the further away the line is observed from the hydrogen tube through the diffraction grating, the longer the wavelength, the lower the frequency, and the lower the energy. During the experiment the red line was the farthest away from the hydrogen tube. According to the data, the change in energy of the red line is significantly smaller than the other two line spectra. This indicates that the red spectra is at a lower energy state. In comparison, the blue-green and violet lines are at higher energy levels where the violet line is at the highest level out of the three. As a result its wavelength is significantly shorter than the other two lines because in theory wavelength and energy are inversely related.  
This relates to the principles of Bohrâs Model. The red line is representative of an electron jumping from energy levels 3 to 2 whereas, green and violet are found at higher energies (energy levels 4 to 2, and 5 to 2 respectively) proved by the data collected in the experiment. According to the Bohr Model, the energy levels of every atom have specific energies. The farther away the energy level is from the nucleus, the more energy it has. In a hydrogen atom, the electron absorbs and releases energy and it jumps back and forth between one energy level and another energy level. This rapid oscillation releases only specific amounts of energy because the electron jumps to fixed points. This released energy produces the line spectrum of red, green/blue and violet in the visible spectrum. 
During this experiment, clear lines of colored light were displayed through the diffraction grating. From their set distances, each wavelength was determined, which helped determine the energy of each line. This signifies how the electrons only existed at these particular energy levels. In conclusion, this experiment has verified that hydrogen atoms follow the Bohr Model in that the electron only moves between certain energy levels, at least in the visible spectrum.
As a result, this experiment proves the quantum model of an atom, where the electron of Hydrogen only exists at set energy values. Energy can only be emitted or absorbed when moving from the levels demonstrated by the lines appeared through the diffraction grating. While moving to higher energy levels, the energy emitted/absorbed by the electron increases, while as a result increases the frequency and decreases the length of the wavelength supported through the results above. Also, this experiment verifies that red spectra contains less energy than its violet and blue-green counterpart.

Error Analysis:
	Though the percent error values were fairly small, there were potential sources of systematic error. Judging by the percent error, the values calculated were accurate overall, not including the results for the blue-green spectra. Since the only variable that can bring drastic changes to individual results is b (Distance from the hydrogen tube to each spectra), most of the errors would be a result of inaccurately measuring bBlue-Green. Tracing through the calculations has to be done in order to see how different b values account for the results
	A smaller result will correspond to a smaller value for frequency (since ÎE = hf, a larger value for the wavelength (since f= cÎ»), and a larger value for b (since Î»=dba2+b2, and b accounts more on the numerator because the denominator is an addition with a square root). Therefore, since the change in energy for the blue-green spectra was smaller than the accepted value, bBlue-Green had to be measured too great
